SIMPLE: grumble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grumble
<hw>Grum"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Grunbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Grumbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. LG.
<ets>grummeln</ets>, <ets>grumen</ets>, D. <ets>grommelen</ets>,
<ets>grommen</ets>, and F. <ets>grommeler</ets>, of German origin; cf.
W. <ets>grwm</ets>, murmur, grumble, surly. ⟦root⟧35. Cf. <er>Grum</er>,
<er>Grim</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To murmur or mutter with
discontent; to make ill-natured complaints in a low voice and a surly
manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>L'Avare, not using half his store,⟦br⟧
Still <qex>grumbles</qex> that he has no more.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To growl; to snarl in deep tones; <as>as, a lion
<ex>grumbling</ex> over his prey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To rumble; to make a low, harsh, and heavy sound; to
mutter; <as>as, the distant thunder <ex>grumbles</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grumble
<hw>Grum"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To express or utter with
grumbling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grumble
<hw>Grum"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The noise of one that
grumbles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A grumbling, discontented disposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A bad case of <qex>grumble</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. H. H.
Jackson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grumbler</ent>⟦br⟧
